<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Rhode Island's solar resource is stronger than many residents realize, with the state receiving approximately 4.2 peak sun hours per day on average throughout the year. This translates to excellent solar production potential, with a typical residential solar panel system generating between 1,100 and 1,400 kilowatt-hours per kilowatt installed annually. The state's coastal location provides consistent solar irradiance with fewer extreme weather events that could damage solar equipment compared to other regions.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Rhode Island show peak production during summer months (May through September) when days are longer and sun angles are optimal. However, even during winter months, solar panels continue to generate significant electricity, often performing better in cooler temperatures. Snow rarely accumulates on properly installed panels due to their angle and smooth surface, and the reflective properties of snow can actually boost production on clear winter days. Most Rhode Island solar installations are oriented south-facing with tilt angles between 30-40 degrees to optimize year-round production.</p>

