<h2>Rhode Island Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Rhode Island offers some of the most comprehensive renewable energy incentives in New England, making solar and efficient HVAC installations highly attractive financially. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit on the total cost of solar panel systems, including equipment and installation, through 2032. This credit can be applied against federal income tax liability and can be carried forward if the credit exceeds taxes owed in the installation year.</p>

<p>The state's Renewable Energy Growth (REG) program provides performance-based incentives for solar installations, offering long-term contracts that pay solar owners for the clean energy they produce. Current REG rates for residential systems range from \$0.285 to \$0.335 per kilowatt-hour produced over 15-20 year terms, providing predictable income streams that significantly improve solar investment returns. The program includes bonus payments for systems that incorporate battery storage or are installed on affordable housing properties.</p>

<p>National Grid offers substantial rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment through their EnergyWise program. Heat pump rebates can reach \$1,250 per ton for qualifying systems with SEER ratings of 15+ and HSPF ratings of 8.5+. Central air conditioning systems qualify for rebates up to \$600, while high-efficiency furnaces can receive rebates up to \$850. The utility also provides enhanced rebates for customers who participate in demand response programs or install smart thermostats.</p>

<p>Additional state programs include property tax exemptions for solar installations, meaning the added home value from solar panels doesn't increase property tax assessments. Rhode Island also offers net metering with full retail rate credits, allowing solar owners to bank excess production during sunny periods to offset usage during cloudy days or peak demand periods. Low-interest financing options are available through the Rhode Island Infrastructure Bank's Efficient Buildings Fund, offering loans up to \$50,000 for qualifying solar and HVAC improvements.</p>

